Using a Monorepo is the most architecturally sound approach for this setup. It allows you to maintain the "Time Planner"
(the logic/UI) and the "2026 Vault" (the data) as a single unit of truth while deploying them to different targets
(Vercel for the UI, Obsidian for the notes).
Here is how you should structure it and why:
1. The Monorepo Structure
You can use Git Submodules or simply move the folders into a single root repository.
text
/ProfoundProjects-Suite (Main Repo)
├── /time-planner-app       # The cloned JS/HTML logic (deployed to Vercel)
│   ├── index.html
│   └── script.js
├── /obsidian-2026-vault    # Your notes and output (Obsidian data)
│   ├── Events/
│   ├── Goals/
│   └── .obsidian/          # Plugin settings & Projects config
└── /sync-engine            # (Optional) Node/Python scripts for automation
Use o código com cuidado.
2. Why this solves your problem:
Unified Deployment: You can deploy the /time-planner-app folder to Vercel/GitHub Pages while the /obsidian-2026-vault 
remains a data directory.
Path Consistency: The "Export System" in your architecture needs to know where to save files. In a monorepo, the script 
can use relative paths (e.g., ../obsidian-2026-vault/Daily/) to find where to write the markdown notes.
Atomic Commits: When you update a feature in the Time Planner that changes the metadata schema (YAML), you can commit 
the code change and the updated notes in the same Git commit.
3. The Synchronization Engine Logic
Since your architecture is currently "Client-side only" (LocalStorage), the monorepo acts as the bridge:
Input: You use the browser UI to plan your time.
Processing: You trigger the Export Flow defined in your architecture.
Output: Instead of downloading a ZIP and manually moving it, a monorepo allows you to eventually use a small Node.js 
script (or a Github Action) to write the JSON data directly into the obsidian-2026-vault folder.
4. Integration with GitHub Projects
By using a monorepo, you can use GitHub Actions as your "Sync Engine":
GitHub Project → Obsidian: An Action can trigger when a GitHub Project card moves, creating/updating a .md file in 
your obsidian-2026-vault folder automatically.
Obsidian → GitHub Project: When you push your notes from Obsidian (using the Git plugin), a GitHub Action can parse
the YAML and update your GitHub Project board.
Recommendation
Yes, move to a monorepo.
Create a new repo called ProfoundProjects-Suite.
Add your Time Planner code into a web-app folder.
Add your 2026 notes into a vault folder.
Point your Obsidian Projects plugin to the vault subfolder.
